{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528844"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:47:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14340"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14340"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.12,0.07,0.03,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61183"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7035"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46630"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"4390"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19560"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61183"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department at 32 weeks gestation with a two-day history of left calf pain and swelling. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her left calf is swollen and tender to palpation. There is no erythema or increased warmth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line investigation for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Venography","D-dimer test","Nuclear medicine ventilation-perfusion scan","Computed tomography pulmonary angiogram","Lower limb compression ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of deep vein thrombosis (DVT) in pregnancy. The most appropriate first-line investigation in this scenario is\u003Cstrong\u003E lower limb compression ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E. It is safe in pregnancy, non-invasive, and has high sensitivity and specificity for proximal DVT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ED-dimer test\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as the first-line investigation for suspected DVT in pregnancy. D-dimer levels are physiologically elevated during pregnancy, reducing the test\u0027s specificity. A negative D-dimer can still be useful to exclude DVT, but it should not be used as the primary diagnostic tool in this population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenography\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that involves injecting contrast material into the veins. While it was once considered the gold standard for diagnosing DVT, it has largely been replaced by non-invasive techniques, especially in pregnancy where radiation exposure is a concern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enuclear medicine ventilation-perfusion scan\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose pulmonary embolism, not DVT. While it may be preferred over CTPA in pregnancy due to lower radiation exposure to the breast tissue, it is not indicated for diagnosing DVT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography pulmonary angiogram (CTPA)\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose pulmonary embolism, not DVT. While patients with DVT can develop pulmonary embolism, this patient does not present with symptoms suggestive of PE (such as chest pain or shortness of breath). Additionally, CTPA involves radiation exposure, which should be avoided in pregnancy if possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while compression ultrasound is the first-line investigation, the overall approach to diagnosing DVT in pregnancy should include clinical probability assessment (such as the LEFt score for pregnancy) in conjunction with imaging. If the initial ultrasound is negative but clinical suspicion remains high, serial ultrasound or additional imaging may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["D-dimer testing has limited utility in pregnancy due to physiological elevation.","Compression ultrasound is the first-line investigation for suspected deep vein thrombosis in pregnancy.","Clinical probability assessment remains important in the diagnostic approach to deep vein thrombosis in pregnancy."],"references":["Kalaitzopoulos DR, Panagopoulos A, Samant S, Ghalib N, Kadillari J, Daniilidis A, et al. Management of venous thromboembolism in pregnancy. Thromb Res. 2022 Mar;211:106-113. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35149395/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46630"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14340"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46630"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T07:29:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T07:31:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7035"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61183"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","syno